## 2. Medical and Health Insurance Claims Data Experience  
## 2. 医疗及健康保险理赔数据经验

### English

I have approximately three years of experience working with medical and pharmacy claims data in real-world evidence, healthcare analytics, and health outcomes research. My work has involved longitudinal insurance records containing diagnosis codes, procedure codes, prescription claims, inpatient and outpatient services, emergency department visits, provider information, enrollment history, place of service, and healthcare cost variables.

I use claims data to identify eligible patients, construct study cohorts, determine index dates, define baseline and follow-up periods, and derive treatment exposures, comorbidities, outcomes, and healthcare utilization measures. I have supported analyses of treatment initiation, switching, discontinuation, adherence, persistence, hospitalization, emergency department use, outpatient visits, specialist services, medication use, and disease-related healthcare utilization.

When analyzing cost data, I distinguish among billed charges, allowed amounts, insurer-paid amounts, patient-paid amounts, and total paid amounts, because these variables represent different economic concepts.

A major part of claims research is establishing continuous enrollment. Continuous insurance coverage helps ensure that the absence of a claim is more reasonably interpreted as the absence of an observed healthcare event rather than loss of data availability.

I also evaluate duplicate claims, adjusted claims, rejected or reversed pharmacy claims, missing provider information, inconsistent dates, and incomplete cost fields. Pharmacy claims often contain reversals or resubmissions, so I apply logic to avoid counting prescriptions that were not ultimately dispensed.

Claims data provide broad population coverage, longitudinal utilization, and relatively complete reimbursed medical activity, but they are generated primarily for billing rather than research. Diagnosis codes may reflect rule-out diagnoses or reimbursement practices. Prescription claims indicate dispensing but not necessarily ingestion. Clinical details such as tumor stage, performance status, laboratory results, imaging findings, and physician reasoning may be missing.

I therefore assess whether claims data are fit for the research question, use validated algorithms where possible, require repeated diagnoses when appropriate, incorporate procedure or medication evidence, link claims with EHR or registry data when available, and perform sensitivity analyses using alternative definitions.

